# pfSense NAT + Firewall plan for Kafka

## Context
- Internal Kafka broker network: `{{ pfsense_nat_network }}`
- WAN interface: `{{ pfsense_wan_interface }}`
- External listener port (per broker): `{{ kafka_external_listener_port }}`

## 1) Create port forwards (NAT)
{% for broker in groups['kafka'] %}
- Forward WAN `{{ hostvars[broker]['kafka_external_ip'] }}:{{ kafka_external_listener_port }}` to `{{ hostvars[broker]['kafka_internal_ip'] | default(hostvars[broker]['ansible_host']) }}:{{ kafka_external_listener_port }}` (TCP)
{% endfor %}

## 2) Create associated firewall rules
- Allow TCP traffic on WAN for each external broker IP and port listed above.
- Restrict source CIDRs to known client networks whenever possible.

## 3) Validate external connectivity
- From a client outside NAT:
  - `kcat -b {{ hostvars[groups['kafka'][0]]['kafka_external_ip'] }}:{{ kafka_external_listener_port }} -L`
- Confirm metadata returns all `EXTERNAL` advertised listeners.

## 4) Security notes
- For production, use SASL_SSL or mTLS listeners.
- Keep management endpoints (`node_exporter`, `jmx_exporter`, SSH) private.
